// Expected lowering of loop_sum/input.c.
//
// Two equivalent forms exist for lowering a C loop. Which one the
// transpiler emits is an open question; both are sketched below.
//
// FORM A — axon as loop state, native Sutra do_while/loop surface
// ---------------------------------------------------------------
// Per the axon spec ("axons appear in exactly four positions" — input
// of function, output of function, start of loop, end of loop), the
// loop's state is an Axon threaded through each iteration. Every
// variable the body references becomes a key on that axon.
//
// This form is the user's recommended pattern (the "cheat way of
// doing tail recursion"). It's robust to side effects the analyzer
// might not catch.
//
//   do_while sum_to_ten_body(a.item("i") < 10, Axon a) {
//       a.item("sum") = a.item("sum") + a.item("i");
//       a.item("i") = a.item("i") + 1;
//       pass a;
//   }
//
//   function int sum_to_ten() {
//       Axon a;
//       a.add("i", 0);
//       a.add("sum", 0);
//       loop sum_to_ten_body(a.item("i") < 10, a);
//       return a.item("sum");
//   }
//
// Status: this surface assumes Sutra's `do_while`/`loop` form accepts
// an Axon-typed state parameter. Today the form supports primitive
// scalar slots; whether `slot Axon a` and Axon-as-loop-state work is
// an open question. The form parses but may need codegen extension
// for the loop machinery to thread axons.
//
// FORM B — slot-per-variable, Sutra's native form
// -----------------------------------------------
// When the loop has only a few primitive-typed variables, the cleanest
// lowering uses Sutra's existing slot-based loop surface directly,
// without going through an axon at all. This form runs end-to-end
// today but doesn't extend to bodies with non-scalar variables.

do_while sum_to_ten_body(i < 10, int i, int sum) {
    pass i + 1, sum + i;
}

function int sum_to_ten() {
    slot int i = 0;
    slot int sum = 0;
    loop sum_to_ten_body(i < 10, i, sum);
    return sum;
}

// Notes:
//   - The transpiler picks Form B when every loop-body variable has a
//     primitive Sutra type (int, float, bool, vector). It picks Form A
//     when the body references something that doesn't have a clean
//     slot type (a struct, a String, a value of unresolved type).
//   - If the user's spec position is "always use the axon form for
//     consistency," the transpiler can be configured to always emit
//     Form A. Form B is then a peephole that could compress an
//     all-scalars axon back into slots — purely an optimization.
